HEADWORD: Pleach
<hw>Pleach</hw> <pr>(pl⟦emac⟧ch)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Pleached</conjf>
<pr>(pl⟦emac⟧cht)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Pleaching</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. OF. <ets>plaissier</ets>
to bend, and also F. <ets>plisser</ets> to plait, L. <ets>plicare</ets>,
<ets>plicitum</ets>, to fold, lay, or wind together. Cf. <er>Plash</er>
to pleach.]</ety> <def>To unite by interweaving, as branches of trees;
to plash; to interlock.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>pleached</xex>
bower.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

